round-color: #ccc;"> talked on Monday</a>=C2=A0about a U.S. Securities and =
Exchange Commission insider trading case against a guy who allegedly worked=
 at a public company (Medivation Inc.), learned through his job that his co=
mpany was about to be acquired, and went out and bought call options on <em=
>another </em>company (Incyte Corp., a biotech company similar to Medivatio=
n), presumably on the theory that:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal=
; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Good news for Medivation would be good for Incyte=E2=80=99s stock, so he=
=E2=80=99d make money, but</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SEC=
 probably wouldn=E2=80=99t go after him for insider trading, because he was=
n=E2=80=99t an Incyte insider.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fi=
rst part was correct =E2=80=94=C2=A0Incyte=E2=80=99s stock went up when Med=
ivation announced its merger, and he made money =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the seco=
nd part was not. The SEC sued him for insider trading, arguing that (1) the=
 information he had was material <em>to Incyte=E2=80=99s stock </em>and (2)=
 he had a duty <em>to Medivation=C2=A0</em>to keep it confidential. This wa=
s a learning experience for all of us, really.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">One thing that I said on Monday is that, while the SEC=E2=80=99s =
argument is not particularly surprising, I had never seen a case like this =
before, and I pondered a bit what that could mean. I suggested two possibil=
ities: Perhaps people just don=E2=80=99t go around using their companies=E2=
=80=99 information to trade on comparable companies, or perhaps they do and=
 the SEC just doesn=E2=80=99t go after them. I guessed that the second poss=
ibility was more likely but I had no real data.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">But here are a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/24851756.270933/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic=
3RyYWN0X2lkPTM2ODkxNTQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb715aa3a" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">paper</a>=C2=A0and <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24851756.270933/aHR0cHM6L=
y9jb3JwZ292Lmxhdy5oYXJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDIwLzEwLzA4L3NoYWRvdy10cmFkaW5nLw/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB4ffc9361" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">blog post</a> from last year, by Mihir Mehta, David Ree=
b and Wanli Zhao, about =E2=80=9CShadow Trading,=E2=80=9D which is =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0this:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We examine wheth=
er corporate insiders attempt to circumvent insider trading restrictions by=
 facilitating trading in competitors and supply chain partners, an activity=
 we label Shadow Trading.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To identify situa=
tions in which insiders could use their private information to facilitate s=
hadow trading, we use corporate announcements. We focus on announcements th=
at are likely to represent the release of private information held by a fir=
m=E2=80=99s insiders such as earnings announcements, M&amp;A transaction an=
nouncements, and announcements about new products. Using multiple proxies o=
f informed trading from the literature to measure shadow trading, we docume=
nt that immediately before one of these corporate news announcements by a f=
ocal firm, competitors and supply chain partners display increased informed=
 trading levels in their stocks. In particular, the magnitude of informed t=
rading is linked to the magnitude of the information shocks. Each news even=
t appears to represent a significant opportunity for profitable trading=E2=
=80=94a back-of-the-envelope calculation suggests that the average profit f=
rom a single shadow trading event ranges from about $140,000 to over $650,0=
00. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Overall, our evidence shows t=
hat employees facilitate trading in their firms=E2=80=99 business partners =
and competitors to circumvent insider trading regulations designed to limit=
 their ability to exploit private information.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">So, yes, the answer is apparently that insiders of one com=
pany regularly use corporate information to trade in the stocks of other co=
mpanies, but the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t usually go after them.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Should it? I dunno. The Incyte/Medivation case looks prett=
y bad: The guy allegedly had the paradigmatic most-material-possible inside=
 information (his company was being acquired at a premium) and used it to t=
rade the paradigmatic most-insider-trader-y-possible instruments (short-dat=
ed out-of-the-money call options). If you look at those facts, you are goin=
g to say =E2=80=9Cyeah this seems like insider trading.=E2=80=9D But=C2=A0<=
em>in general</em>=C2=A0I am not sure it=E2=80=99s so bad for public-compan=
y employees to use things they learn at work to trade in the stocks of othe=
r companies in their industry. A story like =E2=80=9CMs. X is an oil-compan=
y executive at Company Y, through her job she has come to know a lot about =
geology and drilling technologies and the personalities in the sector, she =
met the executives of Company Z at an industry conference and thought that =
they=E2=80=99re a smart crew, she studies maps and geological reports at he=
r job and thinks Company Z owns some good properties, so she bought some Co=
mpany Z stock as an investment=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0I could see how you=
=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>object to that story, but all in all it seems fai=
rly innocuous, more =E2=80=9Ccareful research using expert knowledge=E2=80=
=9D than =E2=80=9Cinsider trading.=E2=80=9D The line between =E2=80=9Csomeo=
ne who works in an industry uses her specialized knowledge to make smart in=
vestments in comparable companies=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cinsider trading=E2=
=80=9D is a bit blurry, and perhaps the SEC should only go after people who=
, you know, buy short-dated out-of-the-money call options on their competit=
ors=C2=A0a couple of days before their company announces a merger.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is one other factor that might have been impo=
rtant in the Medivation/Incyte case. Mehta, Reeb and Zhao write:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We also examine whether firms can directl=
y influence shadow trading activity. Firms have incentives to prohibit thei=
r employees from engaging in shadow trading because the public revelation o=
f such actions could adversely affect their business relationships. Using a=
 subsample of firms for which we can obtain corporate policy handbooks, we =
show that shadow trading activity is relatively lower when firms explicitly=
 mandate prohibitions against it in their employee handbooks.</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Presumably what that looks like is a corpor=
ate insider trading policy that says something like =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=
=99t use what you learn at work to trade our stock or anyone else=E2=80=99s=
,=E2=80=9D as opposed to just =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t use what you learn=
 at work to trade our stock.=E2=80=9D When companies have policies like tha=
t, their employees do in fact do less trading in comparable-company stocks.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact Medivation had that sort of po=
licy. From <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2485175=
6.270933/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMS9jb2=
1wLXByMjAyMS0xNTUucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB24c6af73" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint=
</a> (its emphasis):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Panuwat al=
so signed Medivation=E2=80=99s insider trading policy, which prohibited emp=
loyees from personally profiting from material nonpublic information concer=
ning Medivation by trading in Medivation securities or the securities of an=
other publicly traded company. The policy stated, =E2=80=9CDuring the cours=
e of your employment =E2=80=A6 with the Company, you may receive important =
information that is not yet publicly disseminated =E2=80=A6 about the Compa=
ny. =E2=80=A6 Because of your access to this information, you may be in a p=
osition to profit financially by buying or selling or in some other way dea=
ling in the Company=E2=80=99s securities =E2=80=A6 <strong>or the securitie=
s of another publicly traded company,</strong> including all significant co=
llaborators, customers, partners, suppliers, or competitors of the Company.=
 =E2=80=A6 For anyone to use such information to gain personal benefit =E2=
=80=A6 is illegal. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">What if it hadn=E2=80=99t said that? What if it had said =E2=
=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t use information you get in=C2=A0your job to trade Mediv=
ation stock, but do whatever you want to other stocks=E2=80=9D? Insider tra=
ding, I often say, is not about fairness, but=C2=A0about theft; here the al=
leged theft was from Medivation. The SEC=E2=80=99s theory here is that the =
inside information here was material to Incyte but was misappropriated from=
 Medivation, that the insider had a duty to Medivation to keep it confident=
ial and, because he violated that duty, he broke the law. If he had not had=
 an=C2=A0<em>explicit=C2=A0</em>duty to Medivation not to trade on it, coul=
d the SEC argue the same thing? Maybe? =E2=80=9CYou were supposed to use wh=
at you learned at work to help your company, not to buy call options on com=
petitors.=E2=80=9D (And =E2=80=94 as Mehta et al. point out =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
companies are harmed by this, since it =E2=80=9Ccould adversely affect thei=
r business relationships=E2=80=9D if their executives are privately profiti=
ng from what they learn in negotiations with customers and suppliers, etc.)=
 But it=E2=80=99s a much weaker argument. If Medivation didn=E2=80=99t care=
 that its employees were using inside information to trade on competitors, =
why should the SEC?</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" =
cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
