emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> get it back=
</a>?) Citi appealed, and the=C2=A0appeal is still pending, and I still thi=
nk Citi is going to win in the end because it makes no sense to let the fun=
ds keep the money, but you never know.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24851756.270933/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMTcvY2l0aS=
1jYW4tdC1oYXZlLWl0cy05MDAtbWlsbGlvbi1iYWNr/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d069bb=
6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked=
 about the case</a> in February when the decision came down. The gist is th=
at Citi was the administrative agent for a syndicated loan to Revlon Inc., =
and it accidentally paid off the whole loan early when it meant to just mak=
e an interest payment. The hedge funds who kept the money had reasons of th=
eir own for doing so (involving a dispute over a restructuring of Revlon=E2=
=80=99s debt), but those reasons are not particularly relevant to judge=E2=
=80=99s decision. For his purposes, all that matters is that (1) Revlon rea=
lly owed money to those hedge funds, (2) Citi paid off the amount Revlon=C2=
=A0owed, and (3) the hedge funds thought, for at least a split second, that=
 Citi might have been intentionally paying off the loan on Revlon=E2=80=99s=
 behalf. This is called the =E2=80=9Cdischarge for value defense=E2=80=9D u=
nder New York law, the leading case is something called =E2=80=9CBanque Wor=
ms,=E2=80=9D and you can read more about it in <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24851756.270933/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby=
9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JyQnJRUVBCN19pOC92MA/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB47a0b1bc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">the judge=E2=80=99s opinion</a> but honestly it won=E2=80=99t =
make much more sense if you do.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everyone wa=
s surprised by the decision, it makes no sense, it is not how anyone thinks=
 sophisticated financial counterparties operate, and so it is=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>how sophisticated financial counterparties operate. Basically as=
 soon as the decision came down, bank lawyers starting writing in new syndi=
cated loan documents =E2=80=9Calso if we send you money by accident you hav=
e to send it back, Banque Worms or no Banque Worms.=E2=80=9D And lawyers fo=
r hedge funds and other syndicated lenders did not push back on these claus=
es, because=C2=A0<em>obviously=C2=A0</em>if the bank sends them money by ac=
cident they have to send it back. These clauses are called =E2=80=9CRevlon =
blockers,=E2=80=9D and we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/24851756.270933/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMDMvY2l0aS13b24tdC1taXNwbGFjZS01MDAtbWlsbGlvbi1hZ2Fpbg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3177dc8f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> discussed them in March</a>, a few weeks after the d=
ecision came down. I wrote:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thi=
s doctrine is dumb and no one in the world of syndicated lending actually m=
eant to sign up for it; =E2=80=9Cif you send us the wrong money we will kee=
p it=E2=80=9D is not a rule that anyone wanted built into their loan docume=
nts. It did not occur to anyone to opt out of it=E2=80=94it did not occur t=
o anyone, outside of the small fellowship of Finders Keepers lawyers, that =
this rule even existed=E2=80=94until it cost Citi $500 million. But now eve=
ryone is extremely aware of it, the big banks want to opt out, they have co=
nsulted with their own Finders Keepers lawyers, they have put the opt-out l=
anguage into the contracts, and the other lenders don=E2=80=99t really have=
 a choice. What are they going to do, object? =E2=80=9CNo, if you send us m=
oney by accident, we=E2=80=99d prefer to keep it=E2=80=9D? It=E2=80=99s jus=
t not a reasonable ask. It=E2=80=99s the <em>law</em>, sure=E2=80=94at leas=
t by default=E2=80=94but it=E2=80=99s not reasonable.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s a recent paper by Eric Talley=
 of Columbia Law School called =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24851756.270933/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sM=
y9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTM5MDYyMDE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCceda7b3=
7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Dischar=
ging the Discharge for Value Defense</a>,=E2=80=9D which criticizes the Rev=
lon decision and also counts up the Revlon blockers:</p><blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I document a rapid, precipitous trend towards writing=
 and/or amending debt contracts so as to nullify the Citibank opinion in it=
s entirety, manifested in a variety of =E2=80=9CRevlon blocker=E2=80=9D pro=
visions that have appeared in hundreds of publicly disclosed contracts. The=
 firms that adopt Revlon blockers are systematically the largest and most s=
ophisticated companies in the public markets, and their rejection of Citiba=
nk appears to have met with general market approval.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis analysis underscores the critica=
l role that default rules play in contract law and policy,=E2=80=9D writes =
Talley,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand the high stakes involved in getting them right,=
=E2=80=9D but I am actually not sure the stakes are that high here? I mean,=
 Citi is out $500 million (maybe), so the stakes are high for Citi, though =
presumably Revlon will eventually pay it back even if it loses on appeal. (=
I think?) But the fact that this is a bad=C2=A0<em>rule=C2=A0</em>doesn=E2=
=80=99t matter that much for <em>future=C2=A0</em>cases, because it is a de=
fault rule, and syndicated lenders are big and sophisticated and can just c=
hange their contracts to opt out of the rule.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The funniest part of the paper might be that the judge in the Revlon/Cit=
i case thought the rule=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>important, and that his deci=
sion would cause big good changes in the banking industry. From the paper:<=
/p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The written opinion itself spec=
ulated that lending communities and their trade associations would potentia=
lly alter their practices, for example by effectuating broad changes to com=
pliance staffing, reforms to industry standards, and enhancements to qualit=
y control protocols, so as to further reduce (or in the words of the Court,=
 =E2=80=9Celiminate=E2=80=9D) the possibility of unanticipated mistakes.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And from the opinion:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, there is no doubt that the party be=
st positioned to avoid the error that occurred was Citibank. The bank took =
that role seriously in adopting the six-eye approval process for wire trans=
fers of the kind made here. And while that process obviously failed in this=
 instance, the=C2=A0unprecedented nature of the mistake in this case sugges=
ts that it has generally been successful. Moreover, banks could =E2=80=94 a=
nd, perhaps after this case, will =E2=80=94 take other relatively costless =
steps to both minimize the risk of errors and increase the probability of c=
lawing back erroneous payments. For example, banks could, either on their o=
wn, or through an industry association like the LSTA, create clear standard=
s governing the content and timing of payment notices. If a payment notice =
akin to the Calculation Statements here always preceded an actual payment b=
y some specified interval (and banks adopted security procedures, akin to t=
he six-eyes process, to ensure that they did), then the absence of such a n=
otice would indeed raise a red flag that the payment was erroneous. So too,=
 if such notices always unambiguously and explicitly described the size and=
 nature of the payment, the recipient of a payment that deviated from the n=
otice would plainly be on notice of the mistake. For example, one could ima=
gine payment notices that stated something like: =E2=80=9CYou will shortly =
receive a wire payment of $X. This payment is for interest only; it does no=
t include any payment of principal. If you receive more than $X, any excess=
 would be the result of an error and you would not be entitled to keep it.=
=E2=80=9D Suffice it to say, had the Calculation Statements in this case in=
cluded simple and clear language along these lines, this costly litigation =
would almost surely have been avoided. In short, although the mistake that =
gave rise to this case may be the proverbial Black Swan event, and the risk=
 of a reoccurrence=C2=A0may therefore be small, the banking industry could =
=E2=80=94 and would be wise to =E2=80=94 eliminate the risk altogether by t=
aking these or similarly modest steps.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">The message here is something like =E2=80=9Cbanks need to be=
 more careful with their money, and to teach them a lesson I won=E2=80=99t =
let Citi have its money back.=E2=80=9D And the banks responded, rationally,=
 by changing their contracts so they don=E2=80=99t have to be more careful.=
